ofit on (he investment. even\nthough there had been an appreciation\nin value from March 1, 1*13.\nthe effective date of the first insome\ntax law. in respect to this\nsecond transaction the court merely\nheld in accordance with the admission\nmade recently by Solicitor I\nGeneral Frlerson that an error had\nbeen made in attempting to impose\nft tax where an actual loss on th^ 1\nInvestment had taken place.\nIn the Ryerson. Eldorado and\nGoodrich cases the decisions of the'\nlower courts were favorable to the\ncontention of the government.\nIntricate tonneetlent Cane Wan.\nThe fourth case wan one in which\nthe lower court had decided in\nfavor of the taxpayer. The case\nwan that of James J. Walsh, collector\nof internal revenue in Connecticut.\nagainst Frederick F Brew ter.\nIt involved three different\ntransactions. The decision followed\nthe principles laid down by\nthe court in the Ryerson and Good-1\n?.c^ca!eVnd |B th B,,ner\ndividend decision of March. 190\nSolicitor Genera! Frlerson' In\ncommentng on the decisions said\nthat the government's position h/d'\nBeen completely upheld. He t?. i\nI STfr1 th<! ?f an imP?rtant I\nI nature inasmuch as adverse rulinss'\nwould have meant refunds of mil-1\nlions of dollars of taxes.\nThe Ryerson case involved 1 0001\nshares of capital stock of *n Illinois\ncorporation which was held by!\nthe Merchants Ix>an and Trust Com-\npany of Chicago, as trustee of the1\nestate- of Arthur Ryerson. Vhe I\nstork was valued on March 1, 1913 f\nat $561,000. it was sold on February\n2. 1*17, for fl.280.000 and the\ncoUector of Internal revenue Im-\nK ,'rrVm the *pprollm*,ei\n'\"snwrlr Interpreted.\nIn seeking to recover the tax\npaid upon this amount the Merchants\nLoan and Trust Company\ncontended that the gain in four\nyears of over 1700.000 in an Investment\nof about *500.000 w? ?ot ,nH?\"?*\n\"I'hin the intent of the\nSixteenth amendment to the Con\natitution. c B\nA second contention made by the\nl>l.i?ti?r in the Ryerson casf w?\nli!*1 Word \"lncom?'' ?s used in\nthe Sixteenth amendment and in\nI n!* lBfoma tax o*1 not include\n*ain from capital realised by a\nIngle isolated sale Af property but\nthat only the profit, realised f-om\nsales by one engaged in buying\nand selling as a business?a merbrok'r\nr'a,' e,t?e anent or a\n~r'V??d 'nco,ne whlch\nand\" ?f the Eldorado Coal\n\"0, Co?pany the company\ntL.ii J1' ln,,r\"'? and prac^i'ly*?,u.nd\nfTairs. On th?\nMala of th? fair market value aa\n^,.**.rch the sale of tha\ncaplUl assets resulted In an inf,\n??e?ment on the profit\nthin M ^mOUnt\",? to mnre\n?kJ The court held that\nProfits were properly taxed.\n'?.OOOTOOO Air\nField Soit in Supreme Court\nant*?rr,rrm importyesterdlv\n_ 1 Court\n>eater4ay. which upheld the *ovensment\nIn the matter of tlxa'uon\non profits accruing from the sale\nf capital the follow?^ \"i?\nctsiona were also handed down\nb.y. Jowrr court of |S.'\nto the Cpronado Beach Co I\nfor the seizure by the Federal gov-\nrrarnent for aa aviation base at I\nKbrth Island, la the San Dieco\nCalif harbor, was upheld. The\nflupimwoiTjrwiuw, _\nFears Alien Ru\nGreater Than ii\n\nMark Sullivan Foresee*\nRestriction* Cau*\nImmigrate\nBr 1 ARK JIUIVAJT.\nThe great bulk of the people are\nunder the Impression that something v\ndrastic was done by the recent Con-\ngress to cheek immigration. The\ntruth is nothing whatever was done. h\nIn fact, the net result of the last n\nI Congress is to leave Immigration c;\nunder potentially less check than at u\nany time for four years past.\nDuring the war Congress passed\nan act requiring every Immigrant\ncoming to the United States to have\nhis passport vised by the United 1\nI States consul at the point of de-\nparture. This was a wartime mcas- c\nure. but it was universally held de- p\nsirablo to extend it as a partial t<\ncheck until there shall be a thor- p\nough revision of our immigration tl\nlaws. Congress means to extend it,\nbut did not succeed satisfactorily.\nPassed Conflicting Statute. B\nOn the day.preceding adjournment f,\n?that is. on March 2?Congress n\npassed an amendment to the con- j,\nsular appropriation bill, extending\ni this requirement and appropriating c\n1600.000 to carry it out If Congress b\nhad done this and nothing else, their\nintention would have been safely\ncarried out. But the next day. in E\nthe haste of closing. Congress\npassed a conflicting statute. This\nlatter was a measure repealing all\nwartime legislation. The conflict\nI between the two measures immedi- a\ni ately raised a question, and the two ii\nstatutes were submitted to the At- p\ntorney General for a decision as to tl\n1 which prevails.\nIn that inconclusive state the T\nmatter now stands. For the mo- g\nment. until a decision is made by a\nthe Attorney General, the State De- c,\npartment is taking it for granted e\nthat the regulation stands, and is j,\nstill requiring that passports of im- a\nmigrants be vised. d\nWIImi Let It Die.\nWhat the public generally thinks\nis that a drastic immigration re- 8\nstriction bill was passed by the re- c,\ncent Congress. And so !t was. But tl\nJt was not passed until within ten\ndays of the close of the session. c\nThat made it possible for President n\nWilson to veto it by doing nothing\nabout it. And nothing is exactly c,\nwhat Wilson did. Various expU- li\nnations are given for Wilson's lB\nAUXILIARIES FIRE\nMACHINE GUN INTO\nCATHOLIC CHURCH\n\ns\nNaval Station at King- I\nston Reported Scene\nOf Attack.\n(gpscisl Csble ts Ths Hetald\nsad Ch)ea?? Tribune,i t<\nDUBLIN, ^larch. IS.?Telephone\ncommunication was partly Inter- y\nrupted in Dublin today, when Irish w\nrepublican leaders carried off In- tl\nstruments from a local exchange for\nuse by the volunteer army. V\nTwo minor attacks against crown oi\nforces occurred today. Twenty\n-black and tans\" were attacked on a\nWexford str?et. but with the ex- y\nception of one elderly man wounded r<\nby the 'fire of the military, there\nwere no casualties. The other happened\nnear the North Dublin barracks\nwhen volunteers flred on a\nmilitary lorry.\nIt is reported that thf naval sta- tl\ntion at Kingstown. eight miles tl\nfrom Dublin, was attacked at 11 tl\no'clock last night. Residents of the f<\nlocality heard revolver shots fot- ii\nlowed by bomb explosions and m\nrapid fire lasting for half an hour, a\nMilitary and naval patrols were k\nactive subsequently, but no official\nreport of a fight has Been Issued. a\nWilliam McCarthy, secretary of t\nJ\nCONTINUED ON PAtiE THREE. n\nEFFORTTORESTORE i\nMANCHU RULE SEEN\nsi\nCapture of Urga Is Believed\nPivot on Which New v\nCoup Turns.\ne\n(Special Cable to The Waakiagtoa Herald\naad Chicago Tribune.)\no\nPEK1N, March 28.?Rumors of a c\ntltird attempt to restore the Manchu\ndynasty as the CJ^'nK power in China J\nand of the impending resignation of g\nthe cabinat are disrupting the calm\nwhich aettled over the Internal af-\nfairs of the nation within the past\nsix months.\nThe move to re-establish the empire\nis generally taken to be the outgrowth\nof the capture of Urga early ai\nin February by Baron Ungern. an a(\nassociate of Gen,Setnenoff. the anti- s,\nBolshevist leader in Siberia. Th? w\ncoup waa supposed to bave been ef- w\nfected by Gen. Semenoff after an p|\nagreement with Gen. Chang Tso- tc\nLing. China's present war lord and a\nthe dictator to the republic. dl\nChang has been requested by th?\nChinese government to rush rein* 8f\nforcements to Mongolia to recapture\nUrga. However, be made a counter o|\nrequest for funds to raiae two mor?\nbrigades and in tke meantmie he h\" b.\nbeen holding large birthday celtbration\nas hi* heme in Mukden. It\nIs predicted that Chang may de-\ntnand the restoration of the Manchu\ndynasty srlth himself aa the power cl\nDehind .the throna in return for the J\n?xpulsion of the combined Ruaaian\nind Japanese forces from Mon- J\"\n[oil*.\n(Owiigkt, IML)\nsh Into U. S.\n11 Prewar Days\nDanger In Lifting of\ned by Lack of\n?n Law.\nction. The true one it thai he j\nubmltted It for advice to one of his\nablnet officers. Secretary of Labor\nV'ilson, who has been {generally faorable\nto free immigration. and the\nitter reported that the bill would\ne difficult to carry out, and that. In\n,s opinion, there Isn't any need for j\nestrictlon anyhow. An additional.\nxplanatlon given may be Included\nnder the general description of\nills that die In the l.aate of cloning\navs that It \"was lost In the bhufe\n'because the President did not\nel that he had time to give adeuate\nconsideration to it. All th*\nxnlaimtions com' to the same conluslon.\nnamely, that the bill whion|\nassed the Senate by a vote of ?0\n2. and the. House by 29? to 4?. was\nrevented from becoming n law by j\nt,e President's failure to sign it.\nBack Prewar Ba?l?.\nImmigration today stands exactly\n'here It was before all *&e public\n-ellng arose which everyone\nnought was going to express tself\na law To the extent t?-at it has\neen changed at all. It has been\nhanged toward making it easier,\necause. If the Attorney General Inirprets\nthe conflicting statutes In\navor of the broader one, then we\nhall have lost even that stnall safe-1\nuard'' that lies In the passport re-j\nuirement. j\nThe effort to be more carefuli\nbout Immigration has overwhelm-j\nng public support. Probably the\nuhllc attitude on It la even stronger\nhan the House vote of seven to one. i\nr the Senate vote of thirty to one.\nhe opposition to rcatrlcling Immiration.\nas ahown in the hearings j\nnd in the debates, was practically\nonflned to a small but compact anil\nffective group of large commercial\niterests. and to the Hebrews. whoj\nre the only race whose leaders took\nny organized action in opposition.\nThe fact that among the partv1\nadera and others there Is wideDread\ndaily discussion of what the\nnmlng session will do abet tl.e\niriff and none of immigration,\nrould Indicate that we are more\noncerned about making a little\nloney next year than with the mere\nundamental question of the kind 01\nountry our children will have to\nve in.?\n(Copyright, Ittl.)\n1 COME TO PAY\nRESPECTS,\" IS ALL\nVIVIAN! SAYS\nso ted Frenchman Is Uncommunicative\non Arrival\nin U. S.\n\nNEW YORK. March 2*.?'\"I \"inie\ni the United States to nay th? re- i\npects of France to President Hardig.\"\nwas the only statement Rene\niviani. former premier of France,\nho arrived here this afternoon on\nle liner Lorraine, would make con-,\nerning his mission to America.\nA semiofficial tone was given to\niviani's arrival. Representatives\nf the State Department were arojnd\nle special revenue cutter that\nmded him at a flag-decked pier,\nnd a delegation including Rodman\n/anamaker. Jules Jusserand and I\nspresentatives of the city of New\nork greeted him.\nmes Only l> \"Pay H*a?*ct?.\"\nVlviani reused to discuss hisj\nlission except to issue the follow- j\nlg statement:\n\"I come to pay to the President of J\nlis great republic the respects of\nle French government and the enre\nnation of France. I can there-\n>rc make no statement before nav- j\nIg saluted the Chief of State. In\niluting him I salute also the d^cat,\nnd noble people for whom France\neeps a deep and tender affection.\"\nThe Lorraine reached Quarantine,\ntnoon. The French envoy was\nken off In a revenue Gutter by\names P.eldy. of the State Department,\nand Marcel Knecht, director\nf th< French Bureau of Informa-I\nIon. who Is acting as Mr. Vivlanl'sj\necretary.\nPolice Hold Back Crowd.\nWhen the famous statesman\nmerged from the covered shed at\nhe. pier landing Into the warm sunhtne\nof the Battery he was greeted\ny cheering crowds held back by\nlie police.\nHe walked between Rodman I\n/anamaker and Orover Whalen, of\nle mayor's welcome committee.\naston Llebert. French consul genral.\nwas the first to greet him.\nHe seemed pleased with the ovaon\nand its accompaniment of brass\nand. waving handkerchiefs and\nlicking motion picture cameras.\nArriving at the Vanderbilt Hotel\ne retired Immediately to his suite\nnd It was announced that he would\nee no Interviewers.\nWLF STORM HALTS\nBALLOON HUNTERS\nPENSACOLA. Fla., March 28.? I\ntormy weather on the gulf coast I\ntain interfered with the work of|\naplanes. subchasers and dirigibles\narching for the navy balloon\nhicK disappeared Tuesday night\nIth five men on board. The sealanes\nand dirigible were ordered\nreturn to their station shortly\nfter noon when weather conItions\nbecame threatening.\nNotwithstanding a four-day\narch has failed to develop any\nace of the balloon many naval\nfleers clung to the belief todky\nat the men were alive and would\ns found.\nAs the balloon was of 3.S00 cubic\not capacity and would float for\nlys on the gulf waters, officers deared\nthey believed Chief Quarteraster\nK. W. Wilkinson and his\nur companions Imd unhooked the\ntsket in order to lighten the ga?\nig. climbed Into the rigging and\nera carried t?la?4.\nHarding to Wear\nCarnation Daily\nFor Four Years\nAdopts McKinley Custom\nBut Will Use White\nFlowers, Not Red..\nFtrdlMAii W. Peek, of CfcleHKt,\nsained 'tr+m Pre?Meai\nHard I ns yratrHiij a praptoe to\nwear a wHlte raraatlaa .every\nday f#r the Immr years.\nThe afatllm of (His rnlM\nk7 Ikr PmMnl Hirka iwlbrr\ntry tawiri naaley.\" Prealdeat\nMrKlikr Made It practice\nearly la fela adastalatrattea\nta wear a red earaattaa every\nday aad each rear fela birthday\nla ahaerred hy the display at\nthia hirer.\nMr. Peek waa caaalulwcr\ncacral at the t ailed States ta\nthe Parte expaaltlea la IMS. He\naald yeMerday that fee had ???Bfated\nthat Mr. MeKlalcy wear\na red caraatlaa and that thla\nhad bIvcb hla the Idea af ashlaa\nMr.. Hardlag ta wear a\nnhlte caraatlaa.\nCHILL BLASTS HIT\nCITY AS MERCURY\nDROPS 40 DECREES\nTemperature May Go Below\nFreezing Point After\nSummery Period.\n8trong--northweaterly winds carrying:\nreminders of true Murch\nweather, gripped Washington yesterday\nmid-afternoon, chasing summery\nEaater apparel back to the\nshelves in favor of winter wool. By\n1 midnight the chill blasts had\ndropped the ^nercury more than 40\ndegrees, from midsummer heat at 3\no'clock to a score that laughed as It\nromped near the freealng point.\nWeather officials predicted that\nbusiness-bound Washington would\nread its papers this morning with\ncoat collars turned up and toes feeling\nthe pinch of 2R degrees. The\nmin?r sprinkling of sleet which was\nWashington's In the evening waa\nrecorded as mow in Went Vtrgmla\nWestern Maryland and Pennsylvania.\nForecast for today Is fair and\ncolder, with Wednesday fair ind\nwarmer. The winds are expected to\ncontinue through tomorrow nigh:.\nChicago la Celd Grip.\nCHICAGO. March 28. Freezing\nweather lias wrought havoc in all\nthe parks and thousands of home\ngardens where flowers were in\nbloom, after a month of remarkably\nmild weather. The tail end of the\n10 degrees below zero weather prevalent\nin Western Canada, struek this\nvicinity early last night and tlie\ntemperature has been falling ever\nHince. By daybreak today it had\nfallen to 20 degrees and miles of\ntulips, lilacs and early flower!ng\nwhrubery had turned black. Much\ndamage was also done to the budding\ntrees and prospects for a heavy\ncrop of fruit have been greatly diminished.\nDrop Degree a Minnie.\nSYRACUSE. N.Y.. March 2S?Windriving\nrain storm accompanied by\nhigh winds bordering on a gale\ndrove the temperature down a degree\na minute after 2 o clock this\nafternoon and within half an hour\nthe mcrcury had tumbled from 76\nto 50.\nSYRACUSE. N. Y.. March 2R.Winter,\nstaging a \"comeback.\" rcachod\nSyracuse this afternoon in its Eastward\nsweep. Sno.v began falling in\nmid-afternoon and the temperature\nfell rapidly. 1\nMovie Star Given 10-Day\nJail Term for Speeding\nI.OS ANGELES. March 2R? Be*be\nDaniels, motion picture star, was\nfound guilty of speeding by a jury\nin Judge Cox's court at Santa Ana\nthis afternoon and sentenced to ten\ndays in jail.\nSUje JleMd f\n-TUESDAY, MA\nWEATHER REPORT Page 11\nWASHINGTON*.\