nby their foreign competitors.\nThe Fordney bill provides that the\nconsular Invoice covering merchanflise\nsubject to the act, shall contain\nin addition to the facts and details\nnow required, the foreign\nhome value, or in the absence of\n?uch value, the value to countries\nother than tha United States, or in\nthe absence of such valu^ the coat\nof predition, whan sunk value m\n:ost does not equal the aales price.\nPenalties Are Drastic.\nThe appraiser is directed to rejort\nand return to the collector of\ncustoms a decision as to the foreign\ntome value of all goods or the value\n:o countries other than the United\nstates, or the cost of production as\nhe case may be. and the sale price.\nThe collector shall acertain and fix\nhe amount of the special duty provided\nfor in the act In addition to\nhe duties provided by existing law\nIf an importer refuses to submit\n'or inspection his books or papers\ntertalnlng to the value of any im>orted\nmerchandise, the Secretary of\nhe Treasury may prohibit future\nmportatlons by such person. A\n>enalty of not exceeding $r?,000 is\n>rovlded if an importer gives a relate\nfrom a sales price in order to\n?vade Imposition of an extra duty.\nMay Have Ad Valorem Rates.\nAd valorem rates of duty will be\nised in the new tariff law to\ni greater extent than was anticipated.\nMembers of the subcomnittee\nof the House Ways and\nbfeahs Committee in undertaking\nhe actual draftinc of the bill have\nound it impossible to carry out\n.heir previous plan of returning to\nipeciflc rates. This is chiefly due to\nhe fact that fluctuation in prices\n>f goods has occurred to such an\n>xtent that adequate protection for\nlomestic industries in many cases\nran be assured more readily by ad\nrnlorem rates than by specific rates.\nIn the present Underwood act ad\nralorem rates arc generally applied.\n:hls form of rate being used by\ndemocratic tariff framers usually\n>ecause it is best fitted to a tariff\n'or revenue only*. The Republicans\nire mor