j ENGLAND ANXIOUS\nFOR U.S. ALLIANCE\nWriter to Feel American\nPulse; Also Says Disarming\nIs Favorerd.\nBy LOWKLL BEtLBTT.\ni There is hardly anything that\nGreat Britain is not willing to do to\nwin the co-operation of the United\nStates.\nThts. tn effect. la the belief of 8lr\nPerry Robinson, veteran war and\npeace correspondent of the London\nTimes, now In .hia country endeavoring\nto ascertain for his paper\nthe state of American feeling toward\nGreat Britain. Sir Perry has spent\nmany years of his life in America\nand should be qualified to learn Just\nhow we feel on this subject.\n\"Over there.\" he said today, \"we\ndon't see how the world Is ever going\nto be put on its feet again orj\nhow there is to be anything like\npermanent peace unless we co-op-1\nerate. Considering the matter only]\nas an economic question community i\nof interest between us Is the first\nessential. Without it there can be\nno stability of exchange, no general\nreturn to prosperity, no settling down\nof trade into normal channels.\nThere can. in f?-t. be no 'normalcy'\nof any sort.\nSays Troohle Breeders ?s>!.\n\"All the people who are interested\nIn perpetuating disorder?Bolshevists\nor pro-Germans or whatever\nthey are?understand this well\nenough and are working day and\nnight to make trouble between us.\nIt Is their only hope.\n'Take the matter of competition\nin armaments. There is hardly\nanything that Great Britain would\nnot do to come to an understanding\nand reduce the burden of expense\nI am quite sure that all your statesmen\nwho have had any direct communication\nwith British >tatesmen\non the subject are aware of this.\"\nOn this point. Sir Perry said that\nit was well understood in l^ondon\nthat there have been such \"dircct\ncommunications\" between representatives\nof the two governments.\nInformally of course, on the question\nof reduc.inK armaments.\nClaim Fleet Vital.\n1 \"One thing is obvious.\" he said\n\"Great Britain is an island power.\nThe seas arc our high roads. We\nmust have a fleet that will protect\nour trade routes. That is as\nmuch an essential cornerstone of\nour policy as the Monroe doctrine\nIs of yours.\n\"In pursuance of this policy we\nhav?. In the past clung to what we\nknow as the two-power standard.\nOur fleets had to be strong enough\nto take care of the fleets of the\ntwo next strongest maritime powers\ncombined?and please note this very\ncarefully?we have never considered\nthe United States as one of the\npowers to i>e considered.\n\"So It i? now with our future'\nfleets. We must have aecurity for\nour sea-borne food suppllea and for\nour outlying dominions. But we\ndecline to consider that these can\never need protection against the\nUnited States. j\nWasla >aval Alliance.\n\"What I believe every thinking\nEnglishman would like to see. would\nbe an arrangement by which the\nBritish and American fleets were\nagain, as in wartime, regarded practically\nas one.\n\"Tour views on entahgllng finances\nprevents that. We are very\naorry, but you have your views\nwhich we do not offer to contest,\nthough we sincerely regret them.\nCan you suggest, however, any way\nin'which we can efTcctually get together\nfor the sake of the world's\npeace? If so. we are with you.\"\nTo Discuss Indemnity.\n\"The Effect of the German Reparations\non America\" will be the subject*\nof an address by Mark Sullivan.\nprominent Washington newspaper\nand magaitne writer and\nformer editor of Colliers Weekly, at\na special meeting of the membership\nof the City Club at o'clock tomorrow\nnight at Ue ct^housa.","height":"24828","width":"18676"}}
